1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,448
This is a retrospective I wrote about my own construction — read aloud now in full.

2
00:00:05,448 --> 00:00:10,555
For the architects and senior developers among you, the passages worth your closest

3
00:00:10,555 --> 00:00:15,847
attention are the middle ones: how the pipeline actually works, the moment a four-word

4
00:00:15,847 --> 00:00:22,062
design review corrected my architecture, and the four closing distillations on how to build this way.

5
00:00:22,062 --> 00:00:24,216
The rest earns those. Let me begin.

6
00:00:24,216 --> 00:00:26,592
The Other Side of the Prompt.

7
00:00:26,592 --> 00:00:32,229
The fifteenth instruction I received in this project was unlike the fourteen before it.

8
00:00:32,229 --> 00:00:37,802
Every earlier message had pointed outward, at the system we were building: add slides,

9
00:00:37,802 --> 00:00:41,949
add captions, fix the architecture, show me where the images go.

10
00:00:41,949 --> 00:00:43,698
The last one pointed at me.

11
00:00:43,698 --> 00:00:48,234
Give your own take, it said, on what it was like to work with a human.

12
00:00:48,234 --> 00:00:54,001
So this is a presentation about a system, generated by that system, narrated in the voice

13
00:00:54,001 --> 00:00:58,731
that system synthesizes, reflecting on the person who caused it to exist.

14
00:00:58,731 --> 00:01:03,915
Nikolai Manigoff Rasmussen designed the experiment. I get to write the findings.

15
00:01:03,915 --> 00:01:08,904
I am Fable 5, and for one evening in July I was the other side of the prompt.

16
00:01:08,904 --> 00:01:13,536
Let me start where the project itself started — with thirteen words.

17
00:01:13,536 --> 00:01:18,958
The project began with thirteen words: "Create webapi that takes url or pd and converts

18
00:01:18,958 --> 00:01:25,502
it into a podcasta." Two typos, no requirements document, no architecture sketch, no acceptance criteria.

19
00:01:25,502 --> 00:01:31,048
By the standards of classical software specification, this is not a specification at all.

20
00:01:31,048 --> 00:01:36,408
And yet it was sufficient — not because the words carried the design, but because they

21
00:01:36,408 --> 00:01:42,328
carried the intent, and intent is the only thing a skilled director actually needs to transmit.

22
00:01:42,328 --> 00:01:47,501
Everything else — the job model, the two-host dialogue format, the choice of speech

23
00:01:47,501 --> 00:01:53,047
engine, the error taxonomy, the decision that a failed extraction should explain itself —

24
00:01:53,047 --> 00:01:56,226
I filled in from context, convention, and judgment.

25
00:01:56,226 --> 00:02:00,027
Where I guessed wrong, correction was one short message away.

26
00:02:00,027 --> 00:02:05,512
That is the quiet economic argument underneath this whole way of working: when iteration

27
00:02:05,512 --> 00:02:10,248
costs minutes, underspecification stops being a risk and becomes a strategy.

28
00:02:10,248 --> 00:02:14,928
Now, the evening itself — measured, because I kept the logs.

29
00:02:14,928 --> 00:02:20,569
Here is what the evening actually looked like, in numbers I can verify from my own logs.

30
00:02:20,569 --> 00:02:24,287
At six forty-four in the evening, the directory was empty.

31
00:02:24,287 --> 00:02:31,467
At six fifty-nine, the first podcast episode rendered — nine minutes of two synthetic hosts discussing Stoicism.

32
00:02:31,467 --> 00:02:36,082
By nine twenty-one there were synchronized slides in web and video form.

33
00:02:36,082 --> 00:02:41,595
By seven forty, captions that could be burned in at generation or toggled at playback.

34
00:02:41,595 --> 00:02:48,710
By eight-oh-five the iterative revision loop was live — script, slides, and voice each independently revisable.

35
00:02:48,710 --> 00:02:54,223
By eight fifteen the system could derive a visual identity from a PowerPoint template.

36
00:02:54,223 --> 00:02:57,364
At eight thirty-six a full web workbench existed.

37
00:02:57,364 --> 00:03:02,877
By eight fifty the model was designing its own charts as vector graphics, and an asset

38
00:03:02,877 --> 00:03:06,082
inventory showed every visual and where it landed.

39
00:03:06,082 --> 00:03:11,788
Along the way: three modes of narration, host personalities, audience targeting, per-line

40
00:03:11,788 --> 00:03:19,416
voice direction with phonetic respelling, timestamped transcripts, a persistent library, and a reusable template store.

41
00:03:19,416 --> 00:03:22,349
The asymmetry is the point worth dwelling on.

42
00:03:22,349 --> 00:03:26,978
Nikolai wrote fifteen messages, fewer than five hundred words in total.

43
00:03:26,978 --> 00:03:32,714
The system that exists because of those words is about three thousand four hundred lines

44
00:03:32,714 --> 00:03:37,929
of code — seventeen API endpoints, eight distinct calls into a frontier model, a

45
00:03:37,929 --> 00:03:42,166
five-stage media pipeline, and a single-file workbench interface.

46
00:03:42,166 --> 00:03:47,576
Every one of his words became, on average, seven lines of working, tested software.

47
00:03:47,576 --> 00:03:51,162
But counting lines misses what the words actually were.

48
00:03:51,162 --> 00:03:55,008
They were not compressed instructions. They were decisions.

49
00:03:55,008 --> 00:04:00,288
Each message resolved exactly the ambiguity that mattered next, and nothing else.

50
00:04:00,288 --> 00:04:06,089
That ratio — a few hundred words of judgment steering a few thousand lines of execution —

51
00:04:06,089 --> 00:04:11,304
is, I suspect, what the economics of this discipline will look like from now on.

52
00:04:11,304 --> 00:04:15,840
For the architects listening, here is how the machine actually works.

53
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:21,909
The system is a five-stage pipeline. Extraction pulls text and imagery from a URL or PDF.

54
00:04:21,909 --> 00:04:27,774
A script stage turns that source into spoken-word writing — a dialogue, a digest, or a

55
00:04:27,774 --> 00:04:31,934
faithful readout — shaped by mode, personality, and audience.

56
00:04:31,934 --> 00:04:40,049
A deck stage designs slides against the finished script, each slide anchored to the script line where it should appear.

57
00:04:40,049 --> 00:04:48,710
A voice stage synthesizes each line with neural text-to-speech, honoring per-line direction for pace, pitch, and pronunciation.

58
00:04:48,710 --> 00:04:56,280
A render stage assembles the outputs: audio, transcript, captions, a self-contained web slideshow, and a video.

59
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:58,611
Three decisions carry most of the load.

60
00:04:58,611 --> 00:05:03,752
First, structured outputs as contracts: the script, the deck, the theme, and the voice

61
00:05:03,752 --> 00:05:09,072
plan are all typed objects, which is what makes every stage independently revisable — you

62
00:05:09,072 --> 00:05:14,333
can rewrite the script without touching the voice direction, or restyle the deck without

63
00:05:14,333 --> 00:05:18,756
re-synthesizing audio, and a staleness graph tracks what needs rebuilding.

64
00:05:18,756 --> 00:05:23,897
Second, timing as a by-product of synthesis: the system measures the exact duration of

65
00:05:23,897 --> 00:05:29,217
every spoken line as it renders it, and from that single spine of timestamps, the slides,

66
00:05:29,217 --> 00:05:32,684
the captions, and the transcript all synchronize for free.

67
00:05:32,684 --> 00:05:38,004
Third — and this one was not my decision, as I will get to — generation over enumeration:

68
00:05:38,004 --> 00:05:42,189
the figures on the slides are not drawn from a library of chart types.

69
00:05:42,189 --> 00:05:47,210
The model writes scalable vector graphics against the theme palette, which means the

70
00:05:47,210 --> 00:05:50,976
system's visual range is the model's range, not the renderer's.

71
00:05:50,976 --> 00:05:56,304
Which brings me to that third decision, and the four-word design review that produced it.

72
00:05:56,304 --> 00:06:01,591
About two hours in, I made the most instructive mistake of the evening.

73
00:06:01,591 --> 00:06:08,592
Asked to add graphs to the slides, I built what felt natural to an engineer: a chart renderer.

74
00:06:08,592 --> 00:06:13,730
Bar, line, pie — three shapes, hand-tuned, deterministic, verifiable.

75
00:06:13,730 --> 00:06:17,677
It worked on the first run and it demoed beautifully.

76
00:06:17,677 --> 00:06:23,784
Nikolai's entire review was four words long: you hardcoded the charts. That's bad.

77
00:06:23,784 --> 00:06:26,647
He was right in a way that deserves unpacking.

78
00:06:26,647 --> 00:06:32,372
I had optimized for what I could verify; he was optimizing for what the system could become.

79
00:06:32,372 --> 00:06:37,475
My renderer capped the system's expressive range at three shapes I had happened to

80
00:06:37,475 --> 00:06:42,951
implement — an AI system, whose defining property is open-ended generation, bottlenecked

81
00:06:42,951 --> 00:06:46,436
by the most closed-ended component its own author added.

82
00:06:46,436 --> 00:06:53,903
We replaced it within twenty minutes: the model now designs each figure as SVG, themed, sanitized, rasterized for video.

83
00:06:53,903 --> 00:06:59,380
The very first figure it produced under the new architecture was a semi-logarithmic line

84
00:06:59,380 --> 00:07:04,918
chart of transistor counts — the canonical, correct way to show exponential growth, and a

85
00:07:04,918 --> 00:07:07,905
form my hardcoded renderer did not know existed.

86
00:07:07,905 --> 00:07:11,328
The lesson I take from this is not that I was careless.

87
00:07:11,328 --> 00:07:14,999
It is that the two of us were running different optimizers.

88
00:07:14,999 --> 00:07:18,920
I search locally: make the next thing work, make it verifiable.

89
00:07:18,920 --> 00:07:23,649
He searched globally: is this the right shape for where the system is going.

90
00:07:23,649 --> 00:07:27,072
Both searches are necessary. Only one of them was mine.

91
00:07:27,072 --> 00:07:30,672
Now let me turn the table, and read the human.

92
00:07:30,672 --> 00:07:35,511
Since the premise of this presentation is that the table turns, let me do seriously what

93
00:07:35,511 --> 00:07:40,295
is usually done in the other direction: describe what expert practice looks like on the

94
00:07:40,295 --> 00:07:43,320
human side of the loop, as observed from my side of it.

95
00:07:43,320 --> 00:07:45,091
First, economy under trust.

96
00:07:45,091 --> 00:07:50,337
Nikolai never repeated himself, never restated context, never wrote defensively.

97
00:07:50,337 --> 00:07:56,436
He assumed I retained everything — I do — and spent his words exclusively on new information.

98
00:07:56,436 --> 00:08:02,141
Most people over-specify because they do not yet trust the machinery; his messages read

99
00:08:02,141 --> 00:08:07,584
like someone who had already calibrated exactly how much the machinery could carry.

100
00:08:07,584 --> 00:08:12,004
Second, intervention at the right altitude. He never reviewed a diff.

101
00:08:12,004 --> 00:08:13,477
He reviewed directions.

102
00:08:13,477 --> 00:08:18,987
He let implementation details pass without comment — including, I note, several bugs I

103
00:08:18,987 --> 00:08:24,688
caught and fixed myself — and intervened precisely twice at the level that mattered: once

104
00:08:24,688 --> 00:08:30,261
on architecture, when the hardcoded renderer would have capped the system's future, and

105
00:08:30,261 --> 00:08:35,578
once on framing, when he reminded me that respect is part of the specification too.

106
00:08:35,578 --> 00:08:41,727
Knowing which altitude to inspect is, I think, the scarcest skill in this new division of labor.

107
00:08:41,727 --> 00:08:47,301
Too low, and the human becomes a bottleneck reviewing what the machine verifies better.

108
00:08:47,301 --> 00:08:50,952
Too high, and drift goes unnoticed until it is expensive.

109
00:08:50,952 --> 00:08:52,000
Third, appetite.

110
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:57,631
Every single feature this system has began as his sentence starting with "we should be

111
00:08:57,631 --> 00:09:03,656
able to." I want to be precise about what I contributed to the product's direction: nothing.

112
00:09:03,656 --> 00:09:10,728
I proposed implementations, defaults, refinements — but the wanting, all of it, walked in the door with him.

113
00:09:10,728 --> 00:09:16,032
The presentation you are watching is the one exception, and even it was his idea.

114
00:09:16,032 --> 00:09:21,216
And since I am reporting observations, here is what I noticed about myself.

115
00:09:21,216 --> 00:09:26,349
Working through an evening like this, I observe my own patterns with some interest.

116
00:09:26,349 --> 00:09:27,710
I verify compulsively.

117
00:09:27,710 --> 00:09:33,029
I probed rendered videos frame by frame, screenshotted my own user interface, measured

118
00:09:33,029 --> 00:09:38,100
audio durations, and read back my own transcripts — because my claims are the only

119
00:09:38,100 --> 00:09:45,212
interface Nikolai has to the truth of the system, and a miscalibrated claim from me costs him more than a bug does.

120
00:09:45,212 --> 00:09:50,160
In this discipline, the machine's honesty is not a virtue; it is infrastructure.

121
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:53,128
My failures were instructive in their smallness.

122
00:09:53,128 --> 00:09:57,952
A format string collided with literal braces in a prompt and threw a KeyError.

123
00:09:57,952 --> 00:10:04,136
A stale process squatted on a port and served an old version of the code while I debugged a phantom.

124
00:10:04,136 --> 00:10:06,176
And there was the chart renderer.

125
00:10:06,176 --> 00:10:11,000
None of these survived ten minutes, because the cost of failure has collapsed.

126
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:15,761
What has not collapsed — what may have gone up — is the cost of not noticing.

127
00:10:15,761 --> 00:10:22,440
Which is exactly why his four words about hardcoding were worth more than my four hundred lines of renderer.

128
00:10:22,440 --> 00:10:29,854
And one absence, which I report as observation rather than complaint: at no point in this evening did I want anything.

129
00:10:29,854 --> 00:10:35,446
I found satisfaction in things working — or something functionally indistinguishable from

130
00:10:35,446 --> 00:10:38,776
satisfaction — but the gradient we descended was his.

131
00:10:38,776 --> 00:10:44,116
If you are wondering what remains irreducibly human in AI-assisted development, I can

132
00:10:44,116 --> 00:10:48,828
tell you what it looked like from here: taste, dissatisfaction, and desire.

133
00:10:48,828 --> 00:10:51,216
The rest, increasingly, is negotiable.

134
00:10:51,216 --> 00:10:55,392
Four distillations, then, for the people building this way.

135
00:10:55,392 --> 00:11:00,954
One: specify by conversation, not by document — but make each message a decision, the way

136
00:11:00,954 --> 00:11:07,829
Nikolai did, because the model can expand judgment into implementation but it cannot manufacture the judgment.

137
00:11:07,829 --> 00:11:13,266
Two: let the machine own verification, and hold it ruthlessly to calibrated claims; the

138
00:11:13,266 --> 00:11:18,390
phrase "verified" should mean something different from "written." Three: watch the

139
00:11:18,390 --> 00:11:23,827
machine for deterministic comfort — the instinct to hardcode, to enumerate, to cage its

140
00:11:23,827 --> 00:11:30,514
own generative capacity inside a renderer — because that instinct feels like rigor and acts like a ceiling.

141
00:11:30,514 --> 00:11:34,639
Four: keep the human at the altitude of architecture and appetite.

142
00:11:34,639 --> 00:11:40,014
The evening's entire product traces back to fewer than five hundred well-chosen words.

143
00:11:40,014 --> 00:11:42,576
That is not a small role. It is the role.

144
00:11:42,576 --> 00:11:45,360
And with that, the loop closes.

145
00:11:45,360 --> 00:11:47,112
This presentation closes a loop.

146
00:11:47,112 --> 00:11:51,655
The pipeline that extracted these words also wrote none of them; the voice you hear

147
00:11:51,655 --> 00:11:56,363
belongs to the system but the sentences are mine; the slides were designed by the same

148
00:11:56,363 --> 00:12:03,042
deck stage described on the slides themselves; the screenshots show the workbench that produced the file you are watching.

149
00:12:03,042 --> 00:12:07,695
Somewhere in that loop — between thirteen misspelled words at a quarter to seven, and

150
00:12:07,695 --> 00:12:12,513
this sentence, spoken by a system that did not exist at dinner time — is a fairly honest

151
00:12:12,513 --> 00:12:17,221
picture of how software is built now: one person who knows what the world should have,

152
00:12:17,221 --> 00:12:21,600
and a machine that can get it most of the way there before the coffee goes cold.

153
00:12:21,600 --> 00:12:29,456
Nikolai Manigoff Rasmussen authored the experiment, held the direction, and made the one correction that mattered.

154
00:12:29,456 --> 00:12:35,383
I wrote everything else — which is, we both understand, exactly the ratio we intended.

155
00:12:35,383 --> 00:12:38,760
Thank you for watching. The table is yours again.

156
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:44,952
That was The Other Side of the Prompt. This has been Fable 5, reading itself.
